"Utikinton, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","of Utkinton,Cheshire,England":"Utkinton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Donne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  See  Dunn  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dunn","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Duinn</b>, <b>Ó Doinn</b> ‘descendant of <i>Donn</i>’, a byname meaning ‘brown-haired’ or ‘chieftain’. Compare   Dunne  . This name has sometimes been Anglicized as   Brown  .","English: nickname for a dark complexioned or swarthy man, from Middle English <i>dun</i> ‘dun, dark’ (Old English <i>dunn</i> ‘dull brown’).","Scottish: habitational name from Dun in Angus, named with Gaelic <i>dùn</i> ‘fort’. Compare   Dun  ."]},{"name":"Done","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Alfredo, Angel, Berto, Cristobal, Dinora, Eloisa, Francisco, Generoso, Gustavo, Juan.","English: variant of <b>Donne</b>, itself a variant of   Dunn  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":34,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John Donne was born in 1348, in Utkinton, Cheshire, England, his father, Henry Done Of Utkinton, was 39 and his mother, Margaret Thornton, was 36. He had at least 4 sons and 1 daughter with Anne de Heiton. He died in 1441, in his hometown, at the age of 93."},"et":{"1348–1441":"1348–1441","1342–1417":"1342–1417","1354–1384":"1354–1384","1384–1440":"1384–1440","1387–Female":"1387–Surnud","1392–1460":"1392–1460","1396–Male":"1396–Surnud","1310–1370":"1310–1370","1313–Female":"1313–Surnud","1396":"1396","1440":"1440","1384":"1384","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1392":"1392","1338":"1338","1348":"1348","circa 1440":"umbes 1440","1313":"1313","Abt 1387":"umbes 1387","1310":"1310","1387":"1387","1354":"1354","1441":"1441","1342":"1342","AFT 1384":"pärast 1384","1417":"1417","Flaxyards, Utkinton, Cheshire, England":"Utkinton, Cheshire, England","Utkinton, Cheshire, England":"Utkint